{"parse":{"title":"Amber House","pageid":8351306,"revid":801707566,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">For the novel by Kelly Moore, see <a href=\"/wiki/Amber_House_(novel)\" title=\"Amber House (novel)\">Amber House (novel)</a>.</div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:422px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Amber_House,_Nelson,_New_Zealand,_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg/420px-Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg\" width=\"420\" height=\"315\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg/630px-Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg/840px-Amber_House%2C_Nelson%2C_New_Zealand%2C_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1280\" data-file-height=\"960\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Amber_House,_Nelson,_New_Zealand,_2005-11-16T01-33Z.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>1897 Amber House. (Photo taken from the North-West in late Southern Hemisphere winter with the <a href=\"/wiki/Nelson,_New_Zealand#Centre_of_New_Zealand?\" title=\"Nelson, New Zealand\">Centre of New Zealand</a> visible above the roofline.)</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Amber House</b> is one of the older two storey villas in <a href=\"/wiki/New_Zealand\" title=\"New Zealand\">New Zealand</a>'s third founded city of <a href=\"/wiki/Nelson,_New_Zealand\" title=\"Nelson, New Zealand\">Nelson</a> in the top of the <a href=\"/wiki/South_Island\" title=\"South Island\">South Island</a> at 46 <a href=\"/wiki/Weka\" title=\"Weka\">Weka</a> Street.\n</p><p>It is a traditional colonial-style construction using native <a href=\"/wiki/Dacrydium_cupressinum\" title=\"Dacrydium cupressinum\">Rimu</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Prumnopitys_taxifolia\" title=\"Prumnopitys taxifolia\">Matai</a> timbers with an external <a href=\"/wiki/Brick\" title=\"Brick\">brick</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Chimney\" title=\"Chimney\">chimney</a> that originally served four large fireplaces.\n</p><p>The original, highly decorated, cast iron <a href=\"/wiki/Sewage\" title=\"Sewage\">sewage</a> vent pipes are still intact and visible on the exterior of the building.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Cabragh_House_School\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Cabragh House School</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Original_wallpaper\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Original wallpaper</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Earthquake_resilience\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Earthquake resilience</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Old_English_Walnut_tree\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Old English Walnut tree</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Cabragh_House_School\">Cabragh House School</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Amber_House&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Cabragh House School\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>From 1906 until 1927 Amber House housed a \"Boarding and Day School for Girls and Little Boys\" known as <a href=\"/wiki/Cabragh_House\" title=\"Cabragh House\">Cabragh House School</a> operated by the Hornsby family from <a href=\"/wiki/Ireland\" title=\"Ireland\">Ireland</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Edwardian\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Edwardian\">Edwardian</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Photograph\" title=\"Photograph\">photographs</a> of both the <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.AmberHouse.co.nz/#History\">scholars and the school have been preserved.</a>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Original_wallpaper\">Original wallpaper</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Amber_House&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Original wallpaper\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:300px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Artichoke_wallpaper_Morris_and_Co_J_H_Dearle.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c2/Artichoke_wallpaper_Morris_and_Co_J_H_Dearle.jpg\" width=\"298\" height=\"340\" class=\"thumbimage\" data-file-width=\"298\" data-file-height=\"340\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\">\"Artichoke\" wallpaper designed by <a href=\"/wiki/John_Henry_Dearle\" title=\"John Henry Dearle\">John Henry Dearle</a> for <a href=\"/wiki/Morris_%26_Co.\" title=\"Morris &amp; Co.\">Morris &amp; Co.</a>, <i>circa</i> 1897</div></div></div><p> Amber House preserves a small section of its original unfaded <a href=\"/wiki/Wallpaper_pattern#Group_p1\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Wallpaper pattern\">wallpaper</a> from the late 19th century that was revealed during recent renovations.\n</p><p>Because New Zealand has had for the last two centuries (and continues to have) the highest <a href=\"/wiki/Ultra_violet\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ultra violet\">ultra violet</a> exposure levels of any populated region on earth it is extremely rare to find used (as opposed to unused roll) examples of <a href=\"/wiki/Victorian_era\" title=\"Victorian era\">Victorian era</a> wallpaper in New Zealand that have not faded badly.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Earthquake_resilience\">Earthquake resilience</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Amber_House&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Earthquake resilience\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg/220px-BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"285\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg/330px-BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg/440px-BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"558\" data-file-height=\"724\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:BrickMakingTurnOfTheCentury.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Victorian brick making</div></div></div><p>Of particular interest is the tall brick chimney on the west side of Amber House that has survived major <a href=\"/wiki/Earthquakes\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Earthquakes\">earthquakes</a> in 1929 (<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.teara.govt.nz/EarthSeaAndSky/NaturalHazardsAndDisasters/HistoricEarthquakes/5/en\"><i>Arthur's Pass</i> and <i>Murchison</i></a>), 1968 (<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.teara.govt.nz/EarthSeaAndSky/NaturalHazardsAndDisasters/HistoricEarthquakes/10/en\"><i>\u012anangahua</i></a>) and 1994 without a single crack blemishing its surface.\n</p><p>There has been speculation that, because deep below Amber House are separate beds of <a href=\"/wiki/Shale\" title=\"Shale\">shale</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Sand\" title=\"Sand\">sand</a>, these strata have acted like a naturally occurring analogue of the <a href=\"/wiki/Earthquake_resistant_structure#Wood_frame\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Earthquake resistant structure\">earthquake resistant</a> <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/politics/history-of-parliament/places-and-spaces\">base isolators</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/New_Zealand_Parliament_Buildings#Parliament_House\" title=\"New Zealand Parliament Buildings\">Parliament House</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Wellington\" title=\"Wellington\">Wellington</a> to reduce the incidence of <a href=\"/wiki/Seismic_wave#Types_of_seismic_waves\" title=\"Seismic wave\">short periodicity lateral waves</a> at Amber House during earthquakes.\n</p><p>The evident resilience of this old chimney means that it is even possible that it pre-dates the 1893 magnitude 6.9 Nelson earthquake that moved the spire of <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nelsoncathedral.org/\">Christ Church Cathedral in Nelson</a> nearly a metre out of the vertical plane.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Old_English_Walnut_tree\">Old English Walnut tree</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Amber_House&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Old English Walnut tree\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg/220px-Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"261\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg/330px-Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg/440px-Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"784\" data-file-height=\"929\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Juglans_regia_Broadview.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><a href=\"/wiki/English_Walnut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"English Walnut\">English Walnut</a> Tree in late summer showing the fruits</div></div></div>\n<p>Amber House has the oldest <a href=\"/wiki/English_walnut\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"English walnut\">English Walnut tree (<i>Juglans regia</i>)</a> in the South Island in the back garden. Although old, this venerable tree is relatively small since, when it was originally planted, it would have been only yards from the original shoreline and on very sandy soil with the roots lacking an adequate water supply. This desiccation has resulted in an almost <a href=\"/wiki/Bonsai\" title=\"Bonsai\">Bonsai</a> like effect.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Amber_House&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\"><i>Lucas's Nelson almanac</i>. Lucas. 1927.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Ao